A jet of flames burst from Thassalin's jaws as the colossal Thraki ignited a precise section of the forest, then circled above it for a while, observing. Strangely, as he had slowed down, the strange sounds of screams behind him had ceased. Thassalin had forgotten that he had passengers riding on his back.
"Come on, Tenuk, you've already turned into Thraki before!"
"My flight is very different. I am not lifted roughly by a huge pink dragon!"
"It's not so unpleasant, is it, Kayel?"
Kayel clearly wasn't agreeing with Nyssi; he seemed less black than usual and had dug his claws into Thassalin's back, drawing blood from the Thraki, but apparently, he didn't care much about it. Still, Thassalin realized he had terrified his new friends and found a clearing where they could land.
"My apologies, I detected an odor. I had to check."
"You were obligated to drag us here with you?" Tenuk launched, as he slid down from Thassalin's back along its tail. "And we left Retvik behind! We abandoned our great and strong warrior! How is he going to catch up with us?"
"He'll find a way," retorted Nissy. "Retvik is slow, but not stupid."
"Agreed, but does Retvik know how to drive?"
Nissy blinked and turned towards Tenuk. "Of course he knows how to drive."
Have you ever seen Retvik driving a vehicle? He doesn't have a truck like yours, and I've never seen him drive something as cute as Kayel's little car either. And if he's started coming to work in a car at all, it's only because YOU give us a ride. He just has this bike.
A burst of laughter interrupted them. Thassalin was suddenly hilarious, and nobody understood what made him laugh. It took him a bit too long to calm down.
Here is the translation of the sentence from French to English:  "I AM SORRY, BUT I IMAGINED YOUR GREAT FRIEND IN ARMOR ON A MINIATURE CHILDREN'S BICYCLE. IT WAS SO FUNNY! I WISH I HAD TELEPATHY. THIS IS A PRECIOUS THOUGHT! ONE THAT I CANNOT SHARE!"
Kayel chuckled, imagining what Thassalin was thinking. "Yes, that's right. But what did you pick up and why did you fly off so quickly?"
Thassalin growled, took off and briefly disappeared before returning and dropping a carcass in front of Nyssi. It was an Orothrack, a rare golden and white dragon-like creature. But it was missing its head. "ANOTHER ONE DEAD. I HEAR THEIR CRIES. I FEEL THEIR BLOOD. I AM PROGRAMMED TO PROTECT AND HUNT. AS YISINI DEMANDS. THE CREATURES ARE NEAR."
The powerful Thraki suddenly froze. So did Nyssi and Kayel, their attention drawn by a gap in the clearing. Something large and black was staring at them, hissing. Whatever it was, this thing opened two colossal pairs of wings and charged straight towards Thassalin, showing no concern for the three smaller beings in its path. Kayel and Tenuk managed to take cover just barely, but Nyssi found herself dragged and almost thrown onto Thassalin.
Thassalin reacted to the aggression by catching Nissy and throwing her onto his back using his extraordinarily long and agile tail, before taking off. The two-winged black creature quickly rushed to give chase.
Kayel exhaled as he drew the rifle from his back, then opened a pouch containing a belt of ammunition. He slung the belt over his shoulder for easy access, but quickly realized that Nyssi, the Thraki, and the monster were no longer visible.
"Hey Tenuk, would you like to transform into something that flies?" asked Kayel.
"Do you want to chase them?"
"Yes, of course!"
"But... one of them is a giant monster!"
"And so? I have a super powerful rifle in my hands right now, ready to serve. I just need to see it to shoot at it."
Tenuk hesitated, then stepped back to clear some space for himself. With a low growl slightly strained with discomfort, his body unfolded, his fur was replaced by scales, and his arms turned into wings. He quickly reverted to his usual light blue Thraki form, but his eyes remained red.
The French word "Grimpe" translates to "Climbs" in English. However, it's important to note that context can change the exact form or meaning. If it's part of a sentence, the full context would help to provide a more accurate translation. For example:  - "Il grimpe." translates to "He/she climbs." - "La grimpe" could be "The climb" or "The climbing."  Without additional context, "Grimpe" is best translated as "Climbs."
Having restored Thraki to a more normal appearance, Tenuk now had a back covered in scaled plates, but a pair of spines had also grown on him, useful for Kayel to grip onto. Tenuk needed a bit of time to detach himself, but once airborne, he quickly oriented himself and attempted a pursuit.
However, Tenuk and Kayel quickly realized they were not alone. A second dark creature emerged from below, and Tenuk managed to avoid it barely.
I suppose it's the other big scary monster that was bothering Lanex? Kayel frowned as he tried to aim at the second creature, missed his target, and quickly reloaded his weapon.
Tenuk does not react. He was too focused on his flight towards Nyssi and Thassalin, despite the other creature pursuing them. Kayel awkwardly spun around to face the monster. The fact that it was chasing them was fortunate for Kayel, as it made it easier for him to aim and shoot. Two shots passed through the creature's upper wings, which let out a howl of pain as it disappeared again among the trees. Kayel did not know if she was still following them, but she would certainly not be able to catch up with them.
Further ahead, Nyssi clung desperately, while Thassalin circled in the air, shooting bursts of flames at the blackened monster. Although the creature was clearly wounded, it seemed furious and determined to fight on, and the fireballs did not seem to have the desired effect. When Thassalin straightened up, Nyssi took the opportunity to draw her weapon—a reliable rifle. Of course, it was not designed for this kind of situation, but a burst of shots would surely at least dissuade the black beast, right?
